'''Job for a Cowboy''' is an American [[death metal]] band from [[Glendale, Arizona|Glendale]], [[Arizona]], formed in 2003. The band comprises vocalist Jonny Davy, guitarists Tony Sannicandro and Al Glassman, touring bassist Nick Schendzielos, and drummer Jon "The Charn" Rice. Their debut album ''[[Genesis (Job for a Cowboy album)|Genesis]]'' was released in 2007, peaking at #54 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and selling 13,000&nbsp;copies in its first week of release. The second album, 2009's ''[[Ruination (album)|Ruination]]'',  sold 10,600 copies in the United States in its first week to debut at position No. 42 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart.

The band has played in international music festivals, including [[Download Festival]], [[Mayhem Festival]] and [[Wacken Open Air]].

==History==
===Formation and ''Doom'' (2003<U+2013>2006)===
Job for a Cowboy was founded in [[Glendale, Arizona|Glendale]], [[Arizona]] during December 2003<ref name="metalblade">{{cite web |url=http://www.metalblade.com/english/artists/jobforacowboy/bio.php |title=Job for a Cowboy - Biography|accessdate=19 November 2008 |publisher=Metal Blade Records |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5cS1XNKCt |archivedate=19 November 2008}}</ref> by vocalist Jonny Davy, guitarists Ravi Bhadriraju and Andrew Arcurio, bassist Chad Staples, and drummer Andy Rysdam.<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p826178|pure_url=yes}}|title=Job for a Cowboy > Biography|last=Deming|first=Mark|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Macrovision Corporation]]|accessdate=2008-08-07}}</ref> In 2004, they created a [[MySpace]] profile, posted songs online, and immediately began to connect with several worldwide fans.<ref name="revolvermag">{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/content/job-cowboy |title=Interview with Job for a Cowboy |accessdate=2008-11-14 |last=Epstein |first=Dan |date= |year= |month= |publisher=''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5cKN8CfWt |archivedate=2008-11-14 |quote= }}</ref> Later that year, Staples and Rysdam left Job for a Cowboy and were replaced by Brent Riggs and Elliott Sellers respectively as bassist and drummer.<ref name="allmusic" /> Traffic to the band's MySpace profile increased exponentially in late 2005 when the band released their first [[Extended play|EP]], entitled ''[[Doom (EP)|Doom]]''.<ref name="revolvermag" /> The EP attracted the attention of Arizona independent label King of the Monsters, who distributed the disc after an initial self-released pressing by the band.<ref name="allmusic" />

Job for a Cowboy extensively promoted their debut EP, including three performances on the [[Sounds of the Underground]] tour.<ref name="revolvermag" /> By the end of the year, the band obtained professional management and signed a deal with [[Metal Blade Records]],<ref name="revolvermag" /> who reissued ''Doom'' with a bonus track.<ref name="allmusic" /> During the same year (2006), Arcurio left the band, and Bobby Thompson joined the group.<ref name="allmusic" /> While Job for a Cowboy was writing material for their first full-length album, Sellers announced that he would be leaving the band to go back to school immediately after recording the album.<ref name="revolvermag" /> In search of a permanent drummer, the band then posted a bulletin on [[Blabbermouth.net]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=59682|title=Job for a Cowboy Parts Ways with Drummer, Seeks Replacement|date=2006-10-03|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> which was seen by Jon "The Charn" Rice. He made a video of himself, posted it on [[YouTube]], and sent the link to the band.<ref name="revolvermag" /> Soon after, Rice was incepted into the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=65082|title=Job for a Cowboy Announces New Drummer|date=2007-01-10|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-09-17}}</ref>

===''Genesis'' (2007&ndash;2008)===
In March 2007, Job for a Cowboy completed their debut full-length album, ''[[Genesis (Job for a Cowboy album)|Genesis]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68032|title=Job for a Cowboy Completes Work on New Album 'Genesis'|date=2007-03-01|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-09-17}}</ref> The album was recorded at Blue Light Audio Media in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]] with producer [[Cory Spotts]]. It was mixed by [[Sabbat (band)|Sabbat]] guitarist [[Andy Sneap]]; released on May 15, the album peaked at #54 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and sold nearly 13,000&nbsp;copies in its first week, which made ''Genesis'' the best-selling heavy metal debut since [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'s 1999 [[Slipknot (album)|debut album]].<ref name="revolvermag" /> The album received generally positive reviews, with ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine saying, "an album that quite literally obliterates everyone else currently residing within the death and grind scenes" and "one of the year's most essential metal purchases".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=73180|title=Job for a Cowboy's Debut Has "Exceeded Expectations"|date=2007-05-24|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=Roadrunner Records|accessdate=2008-08-10}}</ref>

In June 2007, the band performed at the [[Download Festival]] in [[Donington Park]], England.<ref name="MU">{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=25526|title=Job For A Cowboy Confirmed For Download Festival and Sounds of the Underground 2007|date=2007-04-16|work=Metal News|publisher=metalunderground.com|accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> The group also played at the [[Sounds of the Underground]] festival along with [[Amon Amarth]], [[Chimaira]], [[Gwar]], and [[Shadows Fall]].<ref name="MU" /> In October, Job for a Cowboy co-headlined the 2007 Radio Rebellion Tour, teaming up with [[Behemoth (band)|Behemoth]], [[Gojira]] and [[Beneath the Massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=78688|title=Job for a Cowboy, Behemoth, Gojira, Beneath the Massacre: North American Dates Announced|date=2007-08-13|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> The band featured on the 2008's [[Gigantour]] with headliners [[Megadeth]], [[Children of Bodom]], [[In Flames]] and [[High on Fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=87515|title=Gigantour Lineup Officially Announced|date=2008-01-01|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> In addition, they have been confirmed for a number of festivals during 2008, including [[Wacken Open Air]] in Germany<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=91118|title=JOB FOR A COWBOY, UNEARTH Confirmed For Germany's WACKEN OPEN AIR Festival|date=2008-02-19|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> and a second appearance at England's Download Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2008.downloadfestival.co.uk/lineup/index.aspx|title=Download Festival 2008: Line Up|publisher=downloadfestival.co.uk|accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> Job for a Cowboy have embarked on a U.S. headlining tour in November and December 2008 with supporting acts [[Hate Eternal]] and [[All Shall Perish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=102777|title=JOB FOR A COWBOY, HATE ETERNAL, ALL SHALL PERISH: U.S. Dates Announced|date=2008-08-13|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=2008-10-28}}</ref> In late-2008 guitarist Ravi Bhadriraju left Job for a Cowboy to return to school because he wanted to pursue a more rewarding career in the medical field, in his words "reinvent the pacemaker"; he was replaced with former [[Despised Icon]] guitarist, Al Glassman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=110772|title=Job for a Cowboy Confirms Guitarist Split, Prepares to Enter Studio|date=2008-12-13|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|accessdate=2008-12-15}}</ref>

=== ''Ruination'' and ''Gloom'' (2009<U+2013>present)===
On May 1, 2009, the band announced that they completed recording their second studio album, ''[[Ruination (album)|Ruination]]'', at AudioHammer studios in [[Sanford, Florida]] with producer [[Jason Suecof]].<ref name="Ruination">{{cite news|url=http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/generalarticlesynopsfullart.aspx?csid1=132&csid2=844&fid1=38222|title=Job for a Cowboy Finish Recording New Album|last=Carman|first=Keith|date=May 1, 2009|publisher=''[[Exclaim!]]''|accessdate=May 13, 2009}}</ref> The album marks the debut of drummer Jon "the Charn" Rice, who has actually been with the band since the tour for ''Genesis'', and also of guitarist Al Glassman.<ref name=
"Ruination" /> ''Ruination'', was then released on July 7, 2009 worldwide through [[Metal Blade Records]].<ref name="Artwork Unveiled">{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=120558|title=Job for a Cowboy: New Album Artwork Unveiled|date={{nowrap|May 21, 2009}}|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|accessdate={{nowrap|May 22, 2009}}}}</ref> The album sold around 10,600 copies in the United States in its first week of release to debut at position No. 42 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=123627 Job for a Cowboy's 'Ruination' Lands On Billboard Chart], blabbermouth.net</ref> Job for a Cowboy took place in the second [[Mayhem Festival]], playing on the [[Hot Topic]] stage along with bands such as [[Cannibal Corpse]] and [[Whitechapel (band)|Whitechapel]]. At the beginning of 2011, the band has stated to work on an EP,<ref name="Peters">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/slayer-manson-unleashing-mayhem-on-tour-1003935163.story|title=Slayer, Manson Unleashing 'Mayhem' on Tour|last=Peters|first=Mitchell|date=January 28, 2009|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=May 13, 2009}}</ref> that was recorded in February at the Audiohammer Studios in Sanford, Florida with producer Jason Suecof.<ref name=EPUnveiled>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=153933|title=JOB FOR A COWBOY Recording New EP Unveiled|date={{nowrap|February 14, 2011}}|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|accessdate={{nowrap|May 22, 2009}}}}</ref>

At the beginning of 2011, the band started work on an EP,<ref name="Peters"/> that was recorded in February at the Audiohammer Studios in Sanford, Florida with producer Jason Suecof.<ref name=EPUnveiled/> Just before the recording of ''Gloom'', bassist Brent Riggs and guitarist Bobby Thompson departed from the band and were replaced by Nick Schendzielos of [[Cephalic Carnage]] and Tony Sannicandro, respectively. On April 13, 2011 a video appeared on the internet of drummer, Jon Rice, performing a new song in the studio.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/job-for-a-cowboy-return/|title=Job For A Cowboy Return!|date={{nowrap|April 13, 2011}}|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|publisher=MetalHammer.co.uk|accessdate={{nowrap|April 28, 2011}}}}</ref> Job for a Cowboy issued their new EP on June 7, 2011, titled ''Gloom'', which was only made available for purchase through mail order and digital download.

==Musical style==
Job for a Cowboy started as a [[deathcore]] group, and evolved into a predominantly death metal sound with their full-length debut ''Genesis''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/jfacowboygenesi.htm|title=Job for a Cowboy - Genesis Review|last=Bowar|first=Chad|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=2008-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Wiederhorn, Jon |year=2008 |month=September |title=Dawn of the Deathcore |journal=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] |issue=72 |pages=pp. 63<U+2013>66 |publisher=[[Future US]] |issn=1527-408X}}</ref> They have been described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as "an Arizona band with a guttural, brute-force sound descended (indirectly) from [[hardcore punk]]"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/20/arts/music/20cowb.html|title=Bringing Chaos to This Part of Universe|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|date=November 20, 2007|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=May 26, 2009}}</ref>
and "straightforwardly brutal act" by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/04/23/megadeth-in-flames-high-on-fire-ground-and-pound-at-gigantour-in-new-york/|title=Megadeth, In Flames, High on Fire Ground and Pound at Gigantour in New York|last=Steffen|first=Chris|date=April 23, 2008|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|accessdate=May 26, 2009}}</ref>

